-- ── Convex ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Convex is a reactive backend-as-a-service platform combining a real-time document database, serverless TypeScript functions, auth, and file storage for full-stack app developers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Convex: Reactive Backend-as-a-Service Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Convex is a reactive backend platform with a real-time database, serverless TypeScript functions, auth, and file storage built for modern full-stack apps.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Convex is a backend-as-a-service (BaaS) platform built around a reactive document database and serverless TypeScript functions, designed to let full-stack developers build real-time, data-driven applications without assembling separate database, API, auth, and caching layers themselves. The company was founded in 2021 by Jamie Turner (CEO), James Cowling (CTO), and Sujay Jayakar, three engineers who previously worked together at Dropbox on large-scale distributed storage and database systems; James Cowling holds a PhD from MIT focused on distributed transaction processing and consensus protocols. Convex is headquartered in San Francisco and has raised venture funding across multiple rounds, including a Series A of roughly $25.7 million led by Andreessen Horowitz with participation from Netlify and Elad Gil, a Series B led by Fifth Wall, Emergence Capital, and GGV Capital, and an additional $24 million round led by a16z and co-led by Spark Capital in late 2025 with participation from Neo, Alumni Ventures, and angel investors including Adam D'Angelo and Drew Houston. Architecturally, Convex centers on a reactive database where queries are TypeScript (or JavaScript) functions that automatically re-run and push updated results to connected clients whenever underlying data changes, eliminating the need for developers to hand-write WebSocket subscriptions, cache invalidation logic, or polling. Application logic is written as three function types deployed directly on Convex's serverless infrastructure: queries (read-only, cached, and reactive), mutations (transactional writes with ACID guarantees), and actions (for calling external APIs or running non-deterministic code). The platform bundles complementary building blocks that would otherwise require separate vendors: built-in authentication integrations (commonly paired with Clerk or Auth0), file storage, scheduled and cron functions, full-text and vector search for AI and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) workloads, and end-to-end TypeScript type safety from the database schema through to the client. A significant differentiator announced in 2024 is that Convex open-sourced its core backend (convex-backend) under the Apache 2.0 license on GitHub, allowing developers to self-host the engine, while the primary commercial product remains the managed cloud offering. Convex's pricing follows a freemium, usage-based structure. The Free (Starter) plan is scale-to-zero and pay-as-you-go, offering generous built-in limits suitable for prototypes, side projects, and early-stage apps, including a fixed monthly allotment of function calls and database storage before usage-based billing kicks in; teams can have multiple free collaborators. The Professional plan uses per-developer seat pricing (around $25 per developer per month) combined with higher built-in resource allowances — larger database storage, I/O, and bandwidth quotas — and lower per-unit overage rates once those built-in limits are exceeded. An Enterprise tier, in active development at the time of research, is aimed at larger organizations needing advanced telemetry, compliance certifications, single sign-on, audit logging, and formal SLAs. Convex also runs a startup program offering up to a year of free Professional-tier access (with no seat fees and discounted usage fees up to a capped amount) to qualifying early-stage companies, a common go-to-market tactic among developer-infrastructure vendors competing for the indie-hacker and YC-adjacent developer audience. Convex's target users are primarily full-stack web and mobile developers — particularly those building with React, Next.js, React Native, and other TypeScript-first frameworks — who want a single reactive backend rather than manually wiring together Postgres, Redis, a pub/sub layer, and a serverless function host. It has also positioned itself for AI-native application development, given its native vector search and support for building agentic workflows with persistent, reactive state. In the competitive landscape, Convex sits alongside other backend-as-a-service and reactive-data platforms such as Firebase (Google), Supabase, PocketBase, and Appwrite, as well as more narrowly-scoped real-time sync engines like Firebase Realtime Database or Ably; it differentiates itself from Supabase and Firebase specifically through its TypeScript-native function model, automatic reactivity without manual subscription wiring, and transactional consistency guarantees on writes. Because the core database engine is open source, Convex also invites comparison to self-hostable backend stacks, even though most users adopt the managed cloud service for its zero-ops convenience. Notable facts include Convex's origin story rooted in the founders' shared experience building and operating Dropbox's storage infrastructure at scale, its early positioning under the tagline of getting developers to 'dump databases' in favor of a higher-level reactive data layer, and its growing emphasis on serving AI agent and RAG-style workloads as a differentiator versus older BaaS incumbents. For a SaaS directory audience, Convex should be understood as a modern, TypeScript-centric alternative to traditional database-plus-API-plus-auth stacks, most relevant to developers building real-time, collaborative, or AI-powered applications who want to minimize backend infrastructure decisions. Note that the name 'Convex' is shared by an unrelated commercial-insurance technology company (Convex Insurance), so buyers researching this backend-as-a-service platform should confirm they are looking at convex.dev and the Jamie Turner/James Cowling/Sujay Jayakar team rather than that separate, unrelated business. Convex's documentation and marketing emphasize a 'sync engine' mental model: rather than developers thinking in terms of REST endpoints and manual cache invalidation, they think in terms of declarative queries that Convex keeps continuously fresh, which is the platform's central pitch to teams evaluating it against hand-rolled Postgres-plus-tRPC-plus-WebSocket stacks. The company continues to invest heavily in its startup and founder-focused go-to-market motion, offering free Professional-tier credits specifically to reduce the up-front cost of adoption for early-stage teams building on React, Next.js, and React Native.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fe42bb0d-0769-4be9-8240-7ea8c6d5d159';

