-- ── Convoy ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Convoy is an open-source, cloud-native webhooks gateway that securely ingests, retries, and delivers webhook events at scale for engineering teams.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Convoy: Open-Source Webhooks Gateway Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Convoy is an open-source, cloud-native webhooks gateway for reliable event delivery, with retries, rate limiting, and self-hosted or cloud deployment.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Convoy is an open-source, cloud-native webhooks gateway built to solve the infrastructure problem of reliably sending and receiving webhook events at scale. It is developed by Frain Technologies (also referred to by its GitHub organization name, frain-dev) and was founded in 2021 by co-founders Subomi Oluwalana (CEO) and Emmanuel Aina, who previously worked together as engineers at Tangerine Africa and other local and international startups before building an API product for fintech companies; repeated customer requests for reliable webhook infrastructure while selling that earlier product directly inspired them to build Convoy. The company went through Y Combinator's Winter 2022 (W22) batch and is headquartered in San Francisco, California, with part of its engineering team based in Lagos, Nigeria. Convoy is written in Go, the same language used to build infrastructure staples like Kubernetes and Prometheus, and is designed to sit at the edge of a company's network as a dedicated webhooks layer: on the outbound side, it ingests events from internal microservices and reliably fans them out to customer-configured endpoints; on the inbound side, it can receive webhooks from third-party providers (such as Stripe or Twilio) and route them to internal services, shielding those internal systems from direct public internet exposure. Core reliability features include automatic retries with configurable backoff, rate limiting per endpoint, circuit breaking to avoid hammering failing endpoints, static outbound IP addresses for allow-listing, rolling/rotating signing secrets for webhook signature verification, event replay and debugging tools, and dead-letter-style handling for events that ultimately cannot be delivered. Convoy has always shipped its core engine as open source with a public roadmap, though its licensing has evolved over time: it originally used the Mozilla Public License 2.0 (MPL 2.0) and later moved toward the Elastic License 2.0 (ELv2) for parts of its codebase, an open-core licensing pattern common among infrastructure startups that need to prevent large cloud providers from directly re-hosting their software as a competing managed service while still keeping the core project source-available and free for self-hosting. Convoy is distributed in three primary ways: a free, self-hosted Community edition that developers can run on their own infrastructure at no license cost; a fully managed Convoy Cloud offering with usage-based, transparent pricing aimed at small teams and startups, with published Cloud pricing starting around $99 per month for a Pro-tier plan; and an Enterprise Partnership Program for large-scale organizations processing more than roughly 20 million webhook events per month, which includes a dedicated customer success team, custom pricing, and a licensed Premium/self-hosted tier obtained through a sales conversation. Convoy's target users are backend and platform engineering teams at companies that either send large volumes of outbound webhooks to their own customers (SaaS platforms, fintechs, e-commerce platforms) or need to reliably ingest and route inbound webhooks from third-party vendors. Because reliable webhook delivery is a deceptively hard distributed-systems problem — requiring retry logic, ordering guarantees, security, observability, and scaling — many engineering teams historically built ad hoc, fragile in-house solutions; Convoy packages this as dedicated, battle-tested infrastructure instead. In the competitive landscape, Convoy competes with other dedicated webhooks-infrastructure vendors such as Svix, Hookdeck, and Novu (for outbound event delivery specifically), as well as broader event-streaming and message-queue platforms like AWS EventBridge, Kafka-based solutions, and various API gateway products that offer webhook-adjacent functionality as a secondary feature. Its open-source, self-hostable nature differentiates it from fully closed SaaS competitors like Svix, appealing particularly to teams with data residency, compliance, or cost-control requirements that make self-hosting attractive, while its managed Cloud option and enterprise support tier let it also compete for customers who prefer a fully outsourced solution. Notable facts include Convoy's origin as a spin-off need discovered while building fintech API infrastructure in the Nigerian and broader African tech ecosystem, its Y Combinator W22 batch membership alongside a large cohort of African startups, and its commitment to keeping a public roadmap and open-source core even as it introduced commercial licensing terms for certain advanced or enterprise features. For a SaaS directory audience, Convoy should be positioned as a specialized, open-source-first webhooks gateway for engineering teams that need production-grade reliability for outbound and inbound event delivery, offering a self-hosted free tier, an accessible paid Cloud plan for smaller teams, and custom enterprise pricing for high-volume organizations. The company has publicly emphasized keeping a generous free tier for individual developers even as it introduced paid Cloud and Enterprise tiers, framing this as a deliberate choice to keep Convoy accessible to the same kind of early-stage, resource-constrained engineering teams its founders once were. Convoy also publishes technical content through its 'Webhooks Blog,' covering both product updates and general webhooks engineering best practices, which it uses to build credibility and inbound interest with the backend engineering audience it targets. Its GitHub repository (frain-dev/convoy) remains the canonical distribution channel for the self-hosted Community edition, and the project maintains a public roadmap so prospective self-hosters and Cloud customers alike can track upcoming feature work before committing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'eb460c74-dce8-4856-9dc3-61f824bd3a75';

