-- ── Copper ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Copper is a CRM built natively for Google Workspace, automatically capturing Gmail, Calendar, and Drive activity to manage sales pipelines with minimal manual data entry.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$23/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$201-500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Copper CRM: The Native Google Workspace CRM$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Copper is a CRM built for Google Workspace, auto-capturing Gmail and Calendar activity to run sales pipelines with less manual data entry. Plans from $23/user.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Copper is a customer relationship management (CRM) platform purpose-built to integrate natively with Google Workspace (Gmail, Calendar, Drive, and Sheets), designed to minimize the manual data entry that plagues typical CRM adoption by automatically capturing contacts, email threads, meetings, and related activity directly from a user's existing Google account. The company was originally founded in 2013 in San Francisco under the name ProsperWorks by Jon Lee, and rebranded to Copper in 2018 as it broadened its focus beyond a narrow Google-Chrome-extension product into a full CRM platform while retaining deep, native Google Workspace integration as its core differentiator. Copper is headquartered in San Francisco, California, and has raised a total of approximately $99.5 million in venture funding across six rounds from investors including Norwest Venture Partners and Industry Ventures, reaching Series C funding status. The company reports serving more than 30,000 businesses and is recognized as a Google-recommended CRM listed prominently in the Google Workspace Marketplace, reflecting a close product and go-to-market partnership with Google. Architecturally, Copper positions itself as a CRM that lives inside Gmail and the broader Google Workspace interface rather than requiring reps to switch context into a separate application: it automatically logs emails, calls, and calendar events against the correct contact or company record, suggests new contacts and leads based on email activity, and syncs bidirectionally with Google Contacts and Calendar. Beyond the Google integration, Copper provides standard CRM capabilities including customizable sales pipelines and deal stages, task and workflow automation to reduce manual follow-up work, lead and opportunity tracking, reporting and forecasting dashboards, email templates and mail merge, and a Chrome extension that surfaces CRM context directly inside the Gmail inbox. It also offers a Copper CRM for Google Sheets integration, letting teams view and edit CRM data from within a spreadsheet interface, and supports integrations with tools like Slack, Zoom, QuickBooks, and various marketing automation platforms via its API and app marketplace. Copper's pricing is structured around three core paid tiers with no permanent free plan, though a 14-day free trial requiring no credit card is available. The Basic plan is priced at $23 per user per month when billed annually (or $29 per user per month billed monthly) and supports up to 2,500 contacts with a limit of 25 custom fields, aimed at small teams that need core pipeline management and task automation. The Professional plan, generally described as Copper's most popular tier, costs $59 per user per month billed annually (or $69 monthly) and raises the contact limit to 15,000 with 50 custom fields, adding more advanced automation and reporting capabilities. The Business plan starts at $99 per user per month billed annually (or $134 monthly), removes the contact cap entirely, and is designed for larger, more established teams that need full customization, advanced reporting, and broader integration options. Annual billing offers meaningful savings — up to roughly 26% — compared to month-to-month pricing across all tiers. Copper's target users are small and mid-size businesses (SMBs) that already run their business operations on Google Workspace and want a CRM that fits into that existing workflow rather than forcing a switch to a Microsoft- or Salesforce-centric ecosystem; it's particularly popular among agencies, consultancies, and relationship-driven B2B sales teams that value low-friction adoption and minimal manual data entry over the deep customizability of enterprise CRM suites. In the competitive CRM landscape, Copper is most frequently compared to HubSpot CRM, Pipedrive, Streak (another Gmail-native CRM), Salesforce Essentials/Starter, and monday.com's sales CRM; its distinguishing position relative to these competitors is its unusually deep, native Google Workspace integration and its lower learning curve for teams already living inside Gmail day-to-day, as opposed to Salesforce's greater configurability and enterprise feature depth or HubSpot's broader all-in-one marketing/sales/service suite. Notable facts include Copper's rebrand from ProsperWorks in 2018 signaling a strategic shift from a Chrome-extension-first product to a standalone SaaS platform, its official Google-recommended CRM status within the Workspace Marketplace, and its reported base of more than 30,000 customer businesses. For a SaaS directory audience, Copper should be framed as the leading CRM choice specifically for Google Workspace-native teams — organizations for whom 'does it work seamlessly with Gmail and Calendar' is a primary CRM selection criterion — rather than as a general-purpose CRM competing on raw customization depth with Salesforce or as an all-in-one marketing suite competing with HubSpot. Copper is particularly popular in relationship-driven verticals such as real estate, consulting, marketing and creative agencies, and professional services firms, where deal cycles are built around ongoing email correspondence and meetings rather than high-volume, transactional outbound selling. Beyond its native Google integrations, Copper connects to broader business tools such as Slack, Zoom, QuickBooks Online, DocuSign, and various marketing automation and e-signature platforms through its API and app marketplace, letting growing teams extend the CRM without abandoning their Google Workspace-centric workflow. Independent review platforms such as G2 and Capterra generally rate Copper highly on ease of use and Google integration specifically, while noting that its customization depth and advanced sales-forecasting capabilities trail more complex, enterprise-oriented CRMs.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'ca95321e-8259-4037-a292-11f90e6c3856';

