-- ── Copy.ai ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Copy.ai is an AI-powered content and workflow automation platform for sales and marketing teams, generating copy, chat responses, and automated GTM workflows.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Memphis, Tennessee, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Copy.ai: AI Content and Sales Workflow Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Copy.ai is an AI writing and workflow automation platform for sales and marketing, offering chat, brand voice training, and automated GTM workflows.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Copy.ai is an AI-powered content generation and go-to-market (GTM) workflow automation platform originally built around AI copywriting and later expanded into broader sales and marketing execution automation. It was founded in 2020 by Paul Yacoubian (CEO) and Chris Lu (CTO), who met and worked together for roughly five years at the ESO Fund, where they helped employees at private, pre-IPO companies such as Stripe and Palantir secure financing to exercise their stock options; that background in venture-adjacent finance rather than a marketing or AI research pedigree is a notable origin detail for the company. Copy.ai is headquartered in Memphis, Tennessee, an atypical location for a venture-backed AI startup compared to the more common San Francisco Bay Area base. The company raised approximately $13.9-19.8 million in total funding across several rounds: a $2.9 million seed round in March 2021 led by Craft Ventures, an $11 million Series A in October 2021 led by Wing Venture Capital with participation from Sequoia Capital, Tiger Global, and angel investor Elad Gil, and a further $3 million convertible note round in November 2023 led by K5 Global Technology. Copy.ai grew rapidly in its early years, reportedly reaching hundreds of thousands of users and multi-million-dollar annual recurring revenue by leveraging product-led growth and a generous free tier. In a major corporate development, Copy.ai was acquired by Fullcast — a revenue operations (RevOps) and go-to-market platform company that also owns Ebsta, Atrium, and Commissionly — in October 2025, with the stated strategic goal of building a unified, AI-native 'Plan-to-Pay' GTM platform spanning sales planning, forecasting, execution, and compensation; Copy.ai's AI content and workflow capabilities are being integrated into Fullcast's Propel product line as the AI execution layer of that broader suite. This acquisition marks a shift for Copy.ai from an independent, venture-backed startup to a component of a larger RevOps software portfolio, which is a materially important fact for any buyer evaluating Copy.ai's long-term roadmap and standalone product direction. Functionally, Copy.ai's platform centers on three pillars: a chat-based AI writing interface for generating marketing copy, sales outreach, and other business content on demand; 'Brand Voice' training, which lets teams feed the AI examples of their own writing so generated content matches a consistent tone and style; and workflow automation, which chains together AI generation steps with data inputs and integrations to automate multi-step GTM tasks such as personalized outbound sequences, proposal generation, and content repurposing at scale, rather than requiring a human to manually prompt the AI for each individual piece of content. The platform supports access to multiple large language models depending on plan tier, and it offers API access and bulk workflow execution on its higher tiers for teams that want to embed Copy.ai's generation capabilities into their own internal tools or pipelines. Copy.ai's pricing follows a classic SaaS freemium model. The Free plan includes 2,000 words of chat generation per month, access to the core chat interface, training for one Brand Voice, and 200 workflow automation credits, with no credit card required to sign up. The Starter (sometimes marketed as Pro) plan costs $49 per month billed monthly (roughly $36 per month if billed annually) for a single seat, unlocking unlimited chat word generation, unlimited chat projects, and access to the platform's full roster of supported LLMs. The Team plan is priced around $249 per month (or roughly $2,232 billed annually), adding unlimited word generation, priority support, and features suited to multi-person marketing and sales teams collaborating on shared workflows. An Enterprise tier offers custom pricing with a guided implementation ('jumpstart'), API access and bulk workflow execution, 20-plus technology integrations, unlimited customizable workflows, and a dedicated account and support team for larger GTM organizations. Copy.ai's target users span solo content creators and small marketing teams using the free or Starter tiers for everyday copywriting, up through sales and RevOps teams at mid-market and enterprise companies using the Team and Enterprise tiers to automate outbound sequences, proposal generation, and other repeatable GTM content workflows. In the competitive landscape, Copy.ai is most frequently compared to Jasper, Writesonic, Rytr, and, more recently, general-purpose AI assistants like ChatGPT and Claude that have eroded the differentiation of dedicated AI copywriting tools; its post-acquisition positioning under Fullcast increasingly differentiates it by embedding AI writing directly into a broader sales execution and RevOps stack (alongside Ebsta's data intelligence and Atrium's analytics) rather than competing purely as a standalone copywriting tool. For a SaaS directory audience, Copy.ai should be described as an AI writing and GTM workflow automation platform now operating as part of Fullcast's RevOps product suite, valuable both to individual users seeking AI-assisted content creation and to sales/marketing organizations seeking to automate multi-step outbound and content workflows at scale. Prior to its acquisition, Copy.ai had reported reaching hundreds of thousands of registered users and multi-million-dollar annual recurring revenue, growth it attributed to an aggressive product-led growth strategy centered on its free tier and viral, template-driven content workflows shared across marketing communities. The Fullcast acquisition explicitly bundles Copy.ai alongside Fullcast's existing RevOps acquisitions — Ebsta for data intelligence, Atrium for sales analytics, and Commissionly for incentive compensation — positioning the combined 'Plan-to-Pay' suite to compete with larger RevOps and sales-engagement platforms such as Outreach, Salesloft, and Clari, which increasingly also embed generative AI content features natively rather than relying on point solutions like standalone AI copywriting tools.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '3c515695-9a2f-4479-901f-6ca785a0e07c';

