-- ── Coral (The Coral Project) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Coral is an open-source commenting and community platform for newsrooms, originally built by Mozilla, the New York Times, and the Washington Post, now developed by Vox Media.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, USA (Vox Media)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$and 20+ other supported languages across deployments$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Coral by Vox Media: Open-Source Newsroom Commenting$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Coral is an open-source commenting and community platform for newsrooms, self-hostable for free or offered as managed hosting by Vox Media.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Coral, commonly known historically as The Coral Project and now branded as Coral by Vox Media, is an open-source content moderation and commenting platform purpose-built for newsrooms and publishers rather than being a generic, off-the-shelf commenting widget. The project was announced in June 2014 as a collaborative initiative between the Mozilla Foundation, The New York Times, and The Washington Post, funded by a grant from the John S. and James L. Knight Foundation, with the explicit goal of rebuilding online comment sections to be more constructive, better moderated, and more useful for both readers and journalists at a time when many publishers were shutting down or restricting comments due to abuse and moderation costs. The project initially developed three distinct tools: 'Trust,' aimed at giving news organizations data-driven ways to identify their best and most trustworthy commenters; 'Ask,' a customizable survey tool for curating conversation and gathering audience input beyond simple comment threads; and 'Talk,' the flagship commenting software designed to look and feel like a modern, thoughtfully moderated comment box rather than a typical unmoderated forum. In January 2019, Vox Media acquired The Coral Project, and the product has since been developed and commercially operated under the 'Coral by Vox Media' brand, with its open-source code hosted on GitHub under the coralproject organization (the flagship 'Talk' repository). Coral's dual-license, open-core-style business model is central to understanding it: the core commenting and moderation software is available as open source and can be downloaded, self-hosted, and run by any publisher at no licensing cost, giving smaller or budget-constrained newsrooms full access to the underlying technology; alternatively, publishers can pay Vox Media for a managed, fully hosted SaaS version of Coral along with implementation services, CMS integration, single sign-on (SSO) integration, ongoing platform maintenance, and strategic partnership support such as engagement strategy consulting and moderation team training. Pricing for the hosted and supported tiers is entirely custom and quote-based — Coral's public pricing page does not list fixed dollar figures, instead directing prospective publisher customers to submit a contact form so the Coral team can scope a package based on traffic volume, comment volume, integration complexity, and the level of support and consulting required. Functionally, Coral's differentiators center on moderation tooling designed specifically for the pressures newsroom comment sections face: AI-assisted comment moderation that helps human moderators triage and prioritize potentially problematic comments rather than reviewing every comment manually, tools to surface and highlight high-quality or 'best' comments to reward constructive engagement, configurable comment stream settings (such as requiring pre-moderation, limiting comment frequency, or closing comments after a set period), integration with CMS platforms so comments appear natively on article pages, and support for anonymous or registered commenting depending on a publisher's editorial policy. Coral is reported to be used by a wide range of publishers globally, including outlets such as The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Post, and The Globe and Mail, and Coral or its earlier Coral Project incarnation has been cited as running comment sections in roughly 30 countries and more than 20 languages, reflecting its adoption well beyond its founding US newsroom partners. Coral's target users are digital newsrooms and publishers of essentially any size — from large national outlets with dedicated moderation staff to small local or nonprofit newsrooms with limited budgets — who want to run reader comments and community engagement without either outsourcing entirely to a generic, ad-supported commenting widget (such as Disqus) or building custom moderation infrastructure from scratch. In the competitive landscape, Coral is most often compared to Disqus (a much larger, generic commenting platform with an advertising-driven free tier), OpenWeb, Viafoura, and various in-house or CMS-native commenting systems; Coral's key differentiation is its journalism-specific design philosophy, its open-source availability for self-hosting (which none of the major generic commenting SaaS competitors offer), and its nonprofit/mission-driven origin story rooted in improving the health of public discourse around news content rather than maximizing pageviews or ad impressions from comment sections. Notable facts include Coral's unusual origin as a foundation-funded, multi-organization collaborative research project rather than a typical venture-backed startup, its acquisition by Vox Media in 2019 which shifted it from a grant-funded nonprofit initiative to a commercially operated product line within a media company, and its continued commitment to keeping the core software open source even after that commercialization. For a SaaS directory audience, Coral should be positioned as the leading open-source, newsroom-specific commenting and community platform, appealing strongly to publishers who value editorial-grade moderation tooling, want the option to self-host for free, or need a vendor whose mission is explicitly aligned with healthy journalism-adjacent discourse rather than general-purpose engagement/ad metrics. Vox Media's own portfolio of digital publications, including The Verge, SB Nation, Eater, and New York Magazine, gives Coral's team direct, first-party operating experience running large-scale, high-traffic comment communities, which the company leverages as a credibility signal when selling the managed hosting and consulting side of the business to external newsroom customers. The original three-tool structure from The Coral Project era — Trust, Ask, and Talk — has since been consolidated into the unified Coral product, with Talk's commenting and moderation functionality remaining the core of what publishers deploy today. Coral's emphasis on reducing moderator burden through AI-assisted triage reflects a broader industry trend of newsrooms needing to do more comment moderation with smaller, cost-constrained community teams, which the platform's tooling is explicitly designed to address.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '67b35559-aa14-4347-b26e-f153e6e02e8c';

