-- ── Coralogix ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Coralogix is a full-stack observability and log analytics platform offering logs, metrics, traces, and cost-optimization tooling on a usage-based pricing model.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tel Aviv (Ramat Gan), Israel$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Coralogix: Full-Stack Observability Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Coralogix is a full-stack observability platform for logs, metrics, and traces with unit-based pricing and TCO Optimizer tools to cut monitoring costs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Coralogix is a full-stack observability and log analytics platform that gives engineering and DevOps teams a unified system for collecting, analyzing, and alerting on logs, metrics, and distributed traces, with a particular emphasis on cost optimization at scale. The company was founded in 2014 by Ariel Assaraf, who serves as CEO, and Yoni Farin, who serves as CTO; Assaraf has described the company's origin as growing out of roughly four years of his own frustration managing unmanageable, sprawling log data before deciding to build a better log analytics platform. Coralogix is headquartered in Ramat Gan, within the greater Tel Aviv area of Israel, and maintains additional global offices in Boston and San Francisco in the United States, Dublin, London, Berlin, Bucharest, and Gurgaon and Bangalore in India, reflecting a globally distributed go-to-market and engineering footprint typical of scaled Israeli enterprise software companies. As of mid-2026, Coralogix employs roughly 500 people worldwide. The company has raised approximately $550 million in total funding, with its most recent and largest round being a $200 million Series F announced in June 2026, co-led by Advent International, CPPIB (Canada Pension Plan Investment Board), and Greenfield Partners, with additional participation from Brighton Park Capital; that round was explicitly framed around scaling Coralogix's observability platform to meet the demands of AI-era infrastructure monitoring. Earlier funding milestones included a $142 million Series D round in 2022 and a $115 million Series E round in 2025. The company reports serving more than 5,000 customers globally, including large enterprise names such as IBM, Tradeweb, and JFrog, and states that its revenue grew more than 60% in the year preceding the Series F raise. Architecturally, Coralogix processes petabytes of production observability data daily across eight global regions, ingesting logs, metrics, and traces from customers' applications and infrastructure and routing that data through configurable pipelines rather than treating all observability data identically. Its signature differentiator is the 'TCO Optimizer' (Total Cost of Ownership Optimizer), a feature that lets teams define policies routing incoming data to different processing and storage tiers based on its business value and query needs — for example, sending high-priority data destined for frequent, real-time search into a 'Frequent Search' tier, sending lower-priority data used mainly for periodic monitoring dashboards into a cheaper 'Monitoring' tier, sending compliance-only data that's rarely queried into an even cheaper 'Compliance' archive tier, or blocking genuinely low-value data at ingestion entirely — all without losing the ability to query that data later if needed, and all without the traditional trade-off of either paying full price to index everything or discarding data outright. This pipeline-based approach to cost management is Coralogix's primary competitive differentiator against observability incumbents that generally charge a flat, high per-GB indexing rate regardless of how frequently the data is actually queried. Coralogix's pricing model reflects this architecture: rather than per-seat, per-host, or flat per-GB pricing, the company uses a unit-based system where one 'unit' is priced at roughly $1.50 and represents a variable quantity of data depending on data type and destination tier — for instance, roughly 1.3 GB of Frequent Search-tier logs might equal one unit, while as much as 3 GB of Monitoring-tier logs might also equal one unit, because Monitoring-tier data costs less per gigabyte to process and store. Customers purchase a committed daily or monthly unit quota, and Coralogix offers a 'Pay-As-You-Go' overage mechanism that lets ingestion continue automatically up to roughly double the committed daily quota when a customer is alerted at 80% utilization, avoiding hard data-loss cutoffs during traffic spikes. There is no permanent free tier, but Coralogix offers a 14-day free trial with no credit card required, providing full feature access and a daily quota of 8 units for evaluation purposes; published G2 reviews from smaller businesses note that the unit-based pricing model, while flexible, can feel complex or comparatively expensive at low data volumes, making Coralogix a better fit for mid-market and enterprise customers with meaningful observability data volume than for very small teams or hobbyist projects. Coralogix's target users are DevOps, SRE, and platform engineering teams at growth-stage and enterprise companies that are either outgrowing the cost structure of legacy observability vendors or need more granular control over what they pay for different classes of monitoring data, particularly as AI-driven infrastructure generates dramatically more observability data volume than traditional application stacks. In the competitive observability landscape, Coralogix is most frequently compared to Datadog, Splunk, Sumo Logic, New Relic, and Grafana Labs/Grafana Cloud, with its core differentiation being the TCO Optimizer's granular, policy-based cost control versus the largely flat or tiered indexing pricing common among competitors like Datadog and Splunk, which has historically driven customer complaints about unpredictable, rapidly scaling observability bills. Notable facts include Coralogix's rapid fundraising acceleration in 2025-2026 explicitly tied to positioning itself as observability infrastructure for the 'age of AI,' its unusually broad global office footprint for a company of its size, and its stated 60%+ year-over-year revenue growth ahead of its Series F raise. For a SaaS directory audience, Coralogix should be positioned as a cost-conscious, full-stack observability platform particularly well suited to engineering organizations with substantial and growing log, metric, and trace volumes who want granular control over observability spend rather than a flat, unpredictable per-GB bill.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '87d8b957-ca86-43e1-bf19-a249b1bd836a';

